So the answer should be approximately 1.48 arcseconds. **Final Answer** The angular resolution of the Spitzer Space telescope is approximately \boxed{1.5} arcseconds. </think> To estimate the angular resolution of the Spitzer Space Telescope, we use the formula for angular resolution in radians, which is given by: \[ \theta \approx 1.22 \times \frac{\lambda}{D} \] where: - \(\lambda\) is the wavelength (5 microns or \(5 \times 10^{-6}\) meters), - \(D\) is the diameter of the telescope (85 cm or 0.85 meters). First, we convert the wavelength to meters and the diameter to meters: - \(\lambda = 5 \times 10^{-6}\) meters, - \(D = 0.85\) meters. Next, we calculate the angular resolution in radians: \[ \theta \approx 1.22 \times \frac{5 \times 10^{-6}}{0.85} \approx 1.22 \times 5.882 \times 10^{-6} \approx 7.16 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \] To convert radians to arcseconds, we use the conversion factor \(1 \text{ radian} \approx 206,265 \text{ arcseconds}\): \[ 7.16 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \times 206,265 \text{ arcseconds/radian} \approx 1.476 \text{ arcseconds} \] Rounding to one decimal place, the angular resolution is approximately: \[ \boxed{1.5} \] arcseconds.
